<statement>
<p>radium-214 has a half-life of 2.46 seconds, and its decay is modeled by <m>\displaystyle{A}={A}_{{0}}{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.46}}}}</m>. If the initial amount is <m>\displaystyle{A}_{{0}}={6.1}</m>, how long will it take until only one third, approximately <m>\displaystyle{A}\approx{2}</m> is left? <fillin characters="5"/></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>3.9</li></ul></p><p><m>\displaystyle{2}={6.1}{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.46}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{1}}{{3}}={\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}^{{\frac{{t}}{{2.46}}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{3}}\right)}}}={\left(\frac{{t}}{{2.46}}\right)}{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{3}}\right)}}}{\left({2.46}\right)}}}{{\ln{{\left(\frac{{1}}{{2}}\right)}}}}={t}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{3.899007751774}\approx{t}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{3.9}\approx{t}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>